\subsection{Regular solutions} \label{sec:reg}
Before we study general solutions, let us present a well-known solutions in Refs.~\cite{Sorkin:1981wd,Pavon1988,Chavanis:2007kn}. 
Most results in this subsection are just reproductions of theirs except a few details.
The purpose of this subsection is to illustrate the role of a solution curve $C$ in $(u,v)$ plane obtained by numerically integrating Eq.~\eqref{dvdu} or \eqref{series}.
The curve $C$ is given in Fig.~\ref{fig:reg} (a).
An important property of the solution curve is its uniqueness.
Any regular distribution of radiation with the boundary data $(R, T, M_R)$ can be described by the one-dimensional solution curve. 

In fact, any point  $(u_R,v_R)= (2M_R/R, 4\pi \sigma R^2 T^4)$ on the solution curve can play the role of a boundary data at $r=R$.

Because of the scale invariance
$(u_{e^s R},v_{e^s R}) = (u_R, v_R)$, a given point $(u_R,v_R)$ represents a one parameter family of boundary data,
$ (e^s M_R, e^s R, e^{-2s} T)$, characterized by the scaling $s$.   

Therefore, the curve $C$ and the scaling span a two dimensional space of boundary data.
This implies that the three parameters $(R,M,T)$ may not be arbitrary but be constrained if the geometry is required to be regular at the center.

A typical mass and density profiles are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:reg} (b). 

